current.planning_8_TEXT: If I have the choice, I would often intentionally oversample since the results of power-analyses, especially for MLM, depend on many parameters that I have high uncertainty about.

With more simple designs/statistical plans, I can usually estimate power and sample size.  However, with most analyses that I do, I consult with a colleague that has that expertise. I typically consult with about 75% of my research.

I do a combination of both consulting with the existing literature, consulting with colleagues who have conducted similar studies or with similar samples/settings and I conduct a power analysis (with support for statistical experts).

Mostly secondary data analysis now, but when I was running studies I got as many groups as possible.  Which in a social science department wasn’t that many (e.g,.. 35 would be good)

End of using ANOVA to grossly estimate effect size

Generally, I don't do power analyses because I analyze data after it has been collected. However, that data was often collected on grants that include some sort of power analysis. I have noticed that many of these analyses justify the sample size that was able to be collected with the budget in the grant---in other words, the budget determines the sample size which determines the power analysis.
I estimate with simple regressions using g power
I do both secondary and primary data collection. When I collect my data, I have either conducted a power analysis or collected as many people as I could given the resources I had.
I ask graduate students and colleagues with expertise for help.
I tend to recruit as large a sample as I can, with a large N at each level.
I will conduct it myself if I can (t-test, ANOVA) but anything more elaborate I will ask someone to help me.
